    <title>Combined summary - Move authorative source for BIPs to git repository</title>
    <updated>2023-06-07T21:51:32.252430+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2013-December/003803.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In December 2013, a new repository was proposed by Wladimir to store Bitcoin Improvement Proposals (BIPs) which was considered more secure than the wiki. The BIPs can be found at https://github.com/bitcoin/bips. It was suggested that BIPs on the wiki should be replaced with links to Github documents and notices that any changes should be proposed on Github or mailed to the BIP editor, gmaxwell to avoid confusion among users. However, Luke-Jr disagreed, saying this would hinder active editing of drafts for some developers, while Gavin Andresen suggested replacing BIPs on the wiki with links to Github documents.Jeff Garzik, a Bitcoin core developer and open-source evangelist at BitPay, Inc., argued that using GitHub would be better due to its primary source status, and mentioned a process for submitting and editing BIPs via email or pull requests on GitHub. Discussions about BIP document storage are being recycled, and the hurdles can be reduced by using a process where the BIPS Editor would receive an email. Additionally, it is suggested that the primary source for storing BIP documents should be a hash-sealed git repo and that the wiki is second class. In an email thread, Gavin Andresen agreed to replace BIPs on the wiki with links to Github documents but requested either Wladimir or Gregory to update BIP 0001 to describe the proper process for creating and editing a BIP since it currently does not mention the GitHub repo. The discussion ended without a consensus, but the repository for BIP documents on GitHub remains active.</summary>
